Evaluate expected significance without any event selection.
Use Poisson statistics for significance calculation.
Calculate the significance of Higgs event happening:
  • we are given that there are 100 Higgs events for each 20,000 QCD events
  • Therefore a probability that there are 100 Higgs events (the probability of 20100 events total is the cdf of the 20,000 Poisson distribution can be found by calculating cdf of the pd for 20,000 median)
  • consequently, to convert to sigma, we need to perform norminv function that gives us sigma from the above probability
pd = makedist('Poisson',20000);
significance = -norminv(1-cdf(pd, 20100))
significance = 0.7112
The result is that the significance is 0.7112 sigma , which is far, far away from regularly accepted 5 sigma significant result.
Compare your number of NHiggs/(NQCD)
Nhiggs = 100; Nqcd = 20000;
ratio = Nhiggs/sqrt(Nqcd)
ratio = 0.7071
The ratio is 0.7071
If they are equivalent, explain your findings.
They are very close in their value because sigma for Poisson distribution can be approximated as sqrt of number of total counts. Therefore when we can calculate how many sigmas are included in our deviation from the medium. (In this case it's 100) so 100/sigma of poisson 20000 = 100/sqrt(20000). Yay.

Now I am going to perform a cut according to both hd2 and invariant mass cuts (t and t2). I've already performed cuts on the data based on mass. Now I am going to update it, cutting off the data that is not within the hd2 cut as well.
First, I calculate the indexes of the QCD data where the d2 is within the cut.
newQCDIndex2(1) = 1;
newQCDlength2 = 1;

Second, I calculate the indexes of Higgs data where d2 is within the cut.
newHiggIndex2(1) = 1;

for i = 1:100000
if (higgData(7,i) > (mhd2-cut2)) && (higgData(7,i) < (mhd2+cut2))
newHiggIndex2(newHlength2) = i;
newHlength2 = newHlength2+1;
end
end
Then I am going to cut off data points where both d2 and mass are within the cut... If the indices of acceptable d2 don't match up with indices of the already within the mass cut indices then I'll cut them off too.
New
Calculate final significance:
finalSignificance = 100*length(newHiggIndex2)/sqrt(2000*length(newQCDIndex2))
finalSignificance = 1.2348e+03
It is bigger by about 300 from just the mass cut! Pretty significant.

Problem 1: High luminosity data
Expected signal is 100*higgData (expected) from lab 7 normalized to have 100,000 points.
Observed data is lowlumi. I am going to plot the mass feature of the low lumi data overlapped with
highlumiMass = highlumi(4, :);
%[counts,centers] = hist(___) returns an additional row vector,
% centers, indicating the location of each bin center on the x-axis.
[C_higgs, Cen_higgs] = hist(hInvariantMass,100);
[C_qcd, Cen_qcd] = hist(qcdInvariantMass,100);
l = length(highlumiMass);
%when I multiply the ratio times the probability of a certain event to
%happen I get the the probability decreases. Then I multiply it by the
%length of highlumiMass array to make it have the same length
C_higgs = C_higgs./sum(C_higgs).*100/20000*l;
C_qcd = C_qcd./sum(C_qcd).*20000/20100*l;
histogram(highlumiMass,100, 'FaceColor',[0 0 0], 'FaceAlpha',0.1);
hold on
bar(Cen_qcd,C_qcd,'FaceColor',[0 1 0], 'FaceAlpha',0.3);
bar(Cen_higgs,C_higgs, 'FaceColor',[0 0 1], 'FaceAlpha',0.7)
title ("Observed vs Signal vs Background data before cut")
legend('highlumi','qcd','higgs')
hold off
As expected, the oserved data looks mostly like background data. We can see the tiny blue higgs expected signal data.
For optimal event selection, we need to maximize data within the cut. Before, we found that the most optimal cut would be in range 125 +/- 1.7
cut = 1.7;
highCutIndex(1) = 0;
highCutLength = 1;
for i = 1:l
if (highlumiMass(i) >= 125-cut) && (highlumiMass(i) <= 125+cut)
highCutIndex(highCutLength) = i;
highCutLength = highCutLength+1;
end
end
%perform the same procedure of stretching it to the previous data as we did
%with background
[C_highlumi, Cen_highlumi] = hist(highlumiMass(highCutIndex));
C_highlumi = C_highlumi./sum(C_highlumi).*l;
bar(Cen_highlumi, C_highlumi, 'FaceColor',[0 0 0], 'FaceAlpha',0.1);
hold on
bar(Cen_qcd,C_qcd,'FaceColor',[0 1 0], 'FaceAlpha',0.3);
bar(Cen_higgs,C_higgs, 'FaceColor',[0 0 1], 'FaceAlpha',0.7)
title ("Observed vs Signal vs Background data after cut (High Luminosity)")
legend('highlumi','qcd','higgs')
hold off
